CrOOH is found naturally in three forms.  They are usually found together with Cr$_{2}$O$_{3}$ in a mineral known as merumite (Milton, 1976): \begin{itemize} \item \href{current_web_home_dir/ABC2_hR4_160_a_a_2a-002}{Grimaldiite, rhombohedral $\alpha$-CrOOH}, \item \href{current_web_home_dir/ABC2_oP8_31_a_a_2a-001}{Guyanaite, orthorhombic $\beta$-CrOOH} (this structure), and \item Bracewellite, orthorhombic $\gamma$-CrOOH is in the \href{current_web_home_dir/AB2C2_oC20_63_c_f_2c-001}{Lepidocrocite ($\gamma$-FeOOH, $E0_{4}$)} structure. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in}
 (Jahn, 2012) give the data for this structure in the $P2_{1}nm$ setting of space group \#31.  We use FINDSYM to transform this to the standard $Pmn2_{1}$ setting. 
 Space group $Pmn2_{1}$ \#31 does not specify the origin of the $z$-axis.  We choose it by setting $z_{1} = 0$ for the position of the chromium atom.
